<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="98" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="98">
<taxonomicName authority="(Gyllenhal, 1835), new to Canada" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Curculio" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Curculio rubidus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubidus">Curculio rubidus (Gyllenhal, 1835), new to Canada</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="98" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="98">Species identification confirmed by RSA, 2015</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="3" pageNumber="98" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="98">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="3" pageNumber="98">
This record comes three years after the first North American detection of the species in Michigan (
<bibRefCitation author="Anderson, RS" journalOrPublisher="The Coleopterists Bulletin" pageId="9" pageNumber="104" pagination="368 - 369" title="Curculiorubidus Gyllenhal, 1836 (Coleoptera: Curculionidae), a European weevil new to North America." url="https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-67.3.368" volume="67" year="2013">Anderson et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
) and is based on the incidental finding in the Montreal area (Notre-Dame-de 
<normalizedToken originalValue="l’Île-Perrot">l'Ile-Perrot</normalizedToken>
) of a single specimen in 2013 and of dozens of additional specimens 2-3 years later. This widespread Palaearctic species is easily separated from all North American native 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Curculio" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Curculio" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Curculio</taxonomicName>
species by its very small size (&lt;3.5mm), lack of femoral teeth and association with birch, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula" order="Fagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Betula</taxonomicName>
L. spp. All specimens recorded in Quebec were collected in a stand of gray birch, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula populifolia" order="Fagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="populifolia">Betula populifolia</taxonomicName>
Marshall (
<taxonomicName family="Betulaceae" lsidName="" pageId="3" pageNumber="98" rank="family">Betulaceae</taxonomicName>
), and most were directly beaten from gray birch. Adults are said to be active from May to October in Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="Hoffmann, A" journalOrPublisher="Federation Francaise des Societes de Sciences Naturelles, Librairie de la Faculte des sciences, Paris, France" pageId="10" pageNumber="105" title="Coleopteres Curculionides (Deuxieme Partie)" volumeTitle="Faune de France" year="1954">Hoffmann 1954</bibRefCitation>
; as &quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Balaninus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Balaninus undulatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undulatus">Balaninus undulatus</taxonomicName>
Herbst, 1795&quot;), but all specimens reported herein were captured in August (except 
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="99" start="start">three</pageBreakToken>
specimens caught on September 1, 2016). This species is also newly recorded from Ontario, based on a specimen photographed by Burke Korol in Barrie, Simcoe County, on August 21, 2015 and posted on bugguide.net (http://bugguide.net/node/view/1127147).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="99" type="specimen data">
